a:1:{i:0;a:4:{s:10:"intro-line";s:50:"Nestled along Tribeca’s 
most hidden street";s:8:"top-copy";s:745:"

Situated on one of Tribeca’s most secret and private streets, Six Cortlandt Alley is an Italianate building that dates back to the mid 1800’s. The alleyway, named after the once prominent Van Cortlandt family, is reminiscent of a mews in London—providing future residents a quiet and discreet location to come and go from their homes. 

Six Cortlandt Alley has been converted into three authentic lofts and two grand penthouses with substantial private outdoor space. The six existing stories will be crowned by a contemporary two-story glass addition. This one-of-a-kind penthouse will command substantial outdoor space, creating a townhouse-like residence perched atop the building. 

";s:5:"image";s:3:"345";s:11:"bottom-copy";s:522:"

The building’s historic fabric is evident both outside and within the condominium. Its two distinct facades, one clad entirely in marble and the other in red brick, have been painstakingly revived by historic restoration experts. 

Upon entering the residential lobby, residents are  greeted with reclaimed heart pine  from the building’s  160 year-old former floor joists, exposed brick walls, and other elements that carry their way up into the residences. 

";}}

a:3:{i:0;a:3:{s:4:"copy";s:379:"

Six Cortlandt Alley’s life has spanned three different centuries, transitioning through a litany of fascinating uses. During the mid1800’s, the building served as the showroom for famed rococo- furniture designer John Henry Belter. It would then operate as a feather exchange in the latter part of the century, as well as a home to the Coraline Corset. 

";s:5:"image";s:3:"357";s:9:"side-copy";s:33:"A former feather exchange venue ";}i:1;a:3:{s:4:"copy";s:547:"

Produced by a company called Werner, the Coraline Corset was ranked in its time by Harper’s Bazaar as one of the top four corsets in the United States. Six Cortlandt Alley would last play home to Diebold—where its now-antique safes were once stored.

The alley and immediate-surrounding area also carry a substantive history, particularly within the art community. Famous artists like Julian Schnable, Keith Haring, David Dalle, Barbara Kruger, and Ross Bleckner all worked in studios on or near Cortlandt Alley. 

";s:5:"image";s:3:"358";s:9:"side-copy";s:23:"Home to Coraline Corset";}i:2;a:3:{s:4:"copy";s:405:"

Bleckner once owned 7 Cortlandt Alley, which is located directly across the street from our lobby entrance. 7 Cortlandt Alley was transformed into the home of the Mudd Club, an avant-garde nightlife venue that operated from 1978 to 1983. The club was a favorite haunt of Andy Warhol, and was frequented by the likes of Madonna, David Bowie, Betsy Johnson, and Jean-Michael Basquiat.   

";s:5:"image";s:0:"";s:9:"side-copy";s:27:"a downtown landmark reborn";}}

a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:"title";s:13:"Living Spaces";s:4:"copy";s:450:"

Our three, full-floor loft residences boast expansive proportions with ceiling heights stretching 10’ and higher in all living spaces. The building’s historic fabric blends seamlessly with modern luxuries, as exposed brick-walls flank an eco-friendly ethanol fireplace with Imperial Danby Marble surrounds, and reclaimed wood window-sills fabricated from the buildings’ former floor-joists adjoin double-pane glass windows.

";s:5:"image";s:3:"369";}}

a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:5:"title";s:8:"Kitchens";s:5:"image";s:3:"374";s:4:"copy";s:420:"

Custom walnut cabinetry milled in the Poconos provide substantial storage and pantry space. Countertops and backsplashes are made from honed Imperial Danby marble quarried in Vermont. A top of the line Wolf appliance package offers a vented five-burner stovetop, double oven and microwave. A 42” integrated double-door refrigerator and separate subzero wine refrigerator come standard in all units. 

";}}

a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:8:"headline";s:42:"A blend of
detailed and
elegant";s:10:"hero-image";s:3:"376";s:5:"title";s:11:"master bath";s:4:"copy";s:451:"

Five-piece master bathrooms are furnished with a glass-walled walk-in shower and separate soaking tub. Floor-to-ceiling Bianco Dolomiti marble wrap every wall, meeting Walnut Brown marble along the floors and tub-shelf. A custom walnut double-vanity with recessed back-lighting is complemented by anodized-bronze fixtures crafted in Brooklyn by Watermark, while floors are inset with radiant heating for a comfortable and spa-like experience.

";s:12:"bottom-image";s:3:"377";}}

cortlandt alley ";s:5:"title";s:15:"master bedrooms";s:10:"hero-image";s:3:"379";s:4:"copy";s:276:"

All four bedrooms are positioned on either Cortlandt Alley or the central light-well, removing residents from the busyness of Manhattan and ensuring silent and quiet nights. The bedrooms are complete with high ceilings and custom built closets with oak wood shelving.

a:1:{i:0;a:3:{s:10:"hero-image";s:3:"381";s:5:"title";s:11:"home office";s:4:"copy";s:214:"

Located between the kitchen and bedrooms, the hoome office presents a customizable space for the residents’ desired use. This final room can be configured as a  playroom, library, or media room.

a:2:{i:0;a:4:{s:5:"title";s:11:"Penthouse A";s:4:"copy";s:795:"

Penthouse A takes up the entirety of the two-story addition being erected upon the building. Like living in a townhouse situated atop the condominiums, this four bedroom/four bathroom duplex residence is a complete architectural departure from the historic fabric of Six Cortlandt Alley. With floor-to-ceiling glass walls and a chamfered glass roof, the living space is exposed to a tremendous amount of sky and light. 

Polaris Quartzite further accentuates the penthouse’s kitchencountertops, backsplash, and the living room’s fireplace surround. This crowning-jewel of Cortlandt Alley boasts over 1,400 square feet of private terrace space in aggregate, including an 1,100 square foot roof terrace with views to the Chrysler and Empire State Buildings.  

";s:18:"floorplan-download";s:3:"334";s:11:"button-text";s:18:"Look at floor plan";}i:1;a:4:{s:5:"title";s:11:"penthouse b";s:4:"copy";s:419:"

Penthouse B occupies the highest level of Six Cortlandt Alley’s original structure. This full-floor loft contains floating stairs that ascend residents onto a 1,283 square foot private rooftop-oasis— the largest contiguous stretch of outdoor space available within the building. This terrace also comes reinforced to accommodate a hot-tub or small lappool, and furnished with a gas gril.  

";s:18:"floorplan-download";s:3:"334";s:11:"button-text";s:0:"";}}
